,"type":"paragraph"},{"text":"<link><caption>There's another important aspect - expectations among businesses, workers and households</caption><url href=\"http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/publications/Documents/quarterlybulletin/2014/qb14q204.pdf\" platform=\"highweb\"/></link>.  If they expect inflation to be, say 2%, then they will set prices and pay deals on that basis and there's a better chance that inflation will be close to the target. ","markupType":"candy_xml","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"That is why you so often hear central bankers discussing how 'well-anchored' public inflation expectations are. The effectiveness of the approach depends to a significant extent on whether the public regards the inflation target and the central bank as 'credible'.","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"id":"81545672","subType":"body","href":"http://news.bbcimg.co.uk/media/images/81545000/jpg/_81545672_miltonfriedman.jpg","path":"/mcs/media/images/81545000/jpg/_81545672_miltonfriedman.jpg","height":351,"width":624,"altText":"Milton Friedman","caption":"Monetarism is seen by many as the brainchild of the late US economist, Milton Friedman","copyrightHolder":"Getty Images","positionHint":"full-width","type":"image"},{"text":"Monetarism and 'shadowing'","markupType":"plain_text","type":"crosshead"},{"text":"The background to the rise of inflation targeting was the problems with alternative methods of containing rising prices. ","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"<link><caption>The International Monetary Fund has described inflation targeting</caption><url href=\"http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/fandd/basics/target.htm\" platform=\"highweb\"/></link> as &quot;a pragmatic response to the failure of other monetary policy regimes&quot;.  ","markupType":"candy_xml","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"There were two main earlier approaches: targets for either the money supply or exchange rates. Britain tried both in the 1980s and early 90s. ","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"In spite of the focus on inflation in their explicit targets, central banks do generally respond to other economic problems","markupType":"plain_text","type":"quote"},{"text":"Money supply targets involve trying to ensure that some measure of money grows at a rate that's consistent with moderate inflation.  <link><caption>It is the approach often known as monetarism,</caption><url href=\"http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/fandd/2014/03/basics.htm\" platform=\"highweb\"/></link> associated particularly with the Nobel Prize winning economist, the late Milton Friedman.  ","markupType":"candy_xml","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"Germany's Bundesbank used this approach for many years.","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"But by the early 1990s the relationship between money supply and inflation was thought to be too erratic to be used as a guide to policy.","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"In 1993, the then <link><caption>chairman of the US Federal Reserve, Alan Greenspan</caption><url href=\"http://www.ny.frb.org/aboutthefed/fedpoint/fed49.html\" platform=\"highweb\"/></link> told Congress: ","markupType":"candy_xml","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"&quot;The historical relationships between money and income, and between money and the price level have largely broken down, depriving the aggregates of much of their usefulness as guides to policy.&quot;","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"In Britain, the policy was replaced with an exchange rate target. At first it was done in a less formal way by 'shadowing' the German mark. Then it became more rigid in 1990 when Britain joined the European exchange rate mechanism (the ERM) a system that kept currency fluctuations within limited 'bands'.","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"The basic idea with this approach is that you can only maintain the exchange rate target if your own inflation is reasonably close to that of the chosen foreign currency. ","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"That ended dismally for Britain with the forced departure from the ERM as a result of massive speculation in the foreign currency markets. ","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"The problem with exchange rate-based inflation policies is that they leave a country with little or no scope to use interest rates to respond to changes in their own economic circumstances. ","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"A few weeks after the ERM debacle came the UK's adoption of inflation targeting. In the British case, the government remained in charge at first, until the responsibility for achieving the target was handed over to the Bank of England in 1997. ","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"id":"81546720","subType":"body","href":"http://news.bbcimg.co.uk/media/images/81546000/jpg/_81546720_mervynking.jpg","path":"/mcs/media/images/81546000/jpg/_81546720_mervynking.jpg","height":351,"width":624,"altText":"Mervyn King, then governor of the Bank of England, pictured 2013","caption":"Central banks should be flexible in targeting inflation, says former Bank of England governor Lord King","copyrightHolder":"Getty Images","positionHint":"full-width","type":"image"},{"text":"'Inflation nutters'","markupType":"plain_text","type":"crosshead"},{"text":"In practice, central banks do not focus exclusively on getting inflation to the target level.","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"Those who think they should do that have been <link><caption>described by the former Bank of England governor Lord (Mervyn) King</caption><url href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304393297000093\" platform=\"highweb\"/></link> as &quot;inflation nutters&quot;.","markupType":"candy_xml","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"Instead what central banks have generally done is known as 'flexible inflation targeting'. ","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"The aim as a rule has not been to keep inflation on target all the time, but to do so over what is called the medium term, which means a few years   ","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"In spite of the focus on inflation in their explicit targets, central banks do generally respond to other economic problems - notably unemployment and weak growth. ","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"The Federal Reserve in the United States was rather late to adopt a specific inflation target <link><caption>(in January 2012</caption><url href=\"http://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/press/monetary/20120125c.htm\" platform=\"highweb\"/></link>). ","markupType":"candy_xml","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"Moderate inflation has long been one of its objectives, part of what is called the Fed's &quot;dual mandate&quot; - maximum employment and stable prices. ","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"It is true there is <link><caption>a third element, moderate long term interest rates,</caption><url href=\"http://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/speech/mishkin20070410a.htm\" platform=\"highweb\"/></link> but it is less discussed and the phrase dual mandate is very widely used.","markupType":"candy_xml","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"For developed countries the target is usually around 2%. That is the figure chosen by the Bank of England and the US Federal Reserve. The European Central Bank aims at just below this target. ","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"id":"81545668","subType":"body","href":"http://news.bbcimg.co.uk/media/images/81545000/jpg/_81545668_markcarney.jpg","path":"/mcs/media/images/81545000/jpg/_81545668_markcarney.jpg","height":351,"width":624,"altText":"Mark Carney","caption":"Critics say inflation targeting has constrained what action the Bank of England can take","copyrightHolder":"Getty Images","positionHint":"full-width","type":"image"},{"text":"Success or not?","markupType":"plain_text","type":"crosshead"},{"text":"So has it worked? In Britain there have certainly been many occasions when the target has been missed by a sufficiently large margin that the <link><caption>governor of the Bank of England has had to write a public letter to the chancellor of the exchequer</caption><url href=\"http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/monetarypolicy/Pages/inflation.aspx\" platform=\"highweb\"/></link> to explain why. ","markupType":"candy_xml","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"The most recent case was because inflation too low, but it has usually been the result of prices rising faster than the target rate.  ","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"There are certainly challenges to what you might call the 'inflation targeting consensus' but so far it has survived them ","markupType":"plain_text","type":"quote"},{"text":"<link><caption>One commentator recently described the target as meaningless</caption><url href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/comment/11226532/Bank-of-Englands-inflation-target-is-now-meaningless.html\" platform=\"highweb\"/></link>.","markupType":"candy_xml","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"But over the longer term inflation has on average been much closer to the objective:  <link><caption>2.1% over 20 years, Lord King has said</caption><url href=\"http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/publications/Documents/speeches/2012/speech606.pdf\" platform=\"highweb\"/></link>. ","markupType":"candy_xml","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"<link><caption>Prof Michael Woodford of Columbia University wrote</caption><url href=\"https://www.imf.org/external/np/seminars/eng/2013/macro2/pdf/mw2.pdf\" platform=\"highweb\"/></link> that inflation targeting &quot;has resulted in a high degree of stability in medium-run inflation expectations during the crisis and its aftermath, and I believe that this has improved the stability of the real economy as well&quot;. ","markupType":"candy_xml","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"Another challenge for the approach is the question of whether it made it harder for central banks to prevent the financial crisis. <link><caption>Prof Jeffrey Frankel of Harvard University argues</caption><url href=\"https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/the-death-of-inflation-targeting\" platform=\"highweb\"/></link> that &quot;in September 2008 it became clear that inflation targeting central banks had not paid enough attention to asset-price bubbles.&quot; ","markupType":"candy_xml","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"He says it should not have been a surprise that boom-bust cycles can happen without inflation ","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"<link><caption>Prof John Quiggin of the University of Queensland Australia</caption><url href=\"http://johnquiggin.com/2012/01/27/inflation-target-tyranny/\" platform=\"highweb\"/></link>, another critic of inflation targets, says &quot;central banks have failed, disastrously, and admitting this would be the first step towards a sustainable recovery&quot;.","markupType":"candy_xml","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"Another complaint is that inflation targeting as in the UK - where it is the only explicit objective for monetary policy - constrained the Bank of England in the aftermath of the financial crisis. ","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"<link><caption>Prof Simon Wren-Lewis of Oxford told the House of Commons Treasury Committee</caption><url href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-committees/treasury/MarkCarneyEvidence.pdf\" platform=\"highweb\"/></link> in 2012, that &quot;policy is providing insufficient stimulus to the UK economy now, because of the form of the current monetary policy regime&quot;.","markupType":"candy_xml","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"He suggested exploring alternatives including something akin to the US Fed's dual mandate. ","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"Prof Karl Whelan of University College Dublin wrote &quot;the Crisis has ruined inflation targeting's 'wonder drug' reputation&quot;. ","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"id":"81546722","subType":"body","href":"http://news.bbcimg.co.uk/media/images/81546000/jpg/_81546722_shoppers.jpg","path":"/mcs/media/images/81546000/jpg/_81546722_shoppers.jpg","height":351,"width":624,"altText":"shoppers","caption":"Boom-bust cycles can happen without inflation, say critics of inflation-targeting","copyrightHolder":"Getty Images","positionHint":"full-width","type":"image"},{"text":"Needed 'more than ever'","markupType":"plain_text","type":"crosshead"},{"text":"But there are plenty of supporters. <link><caption>A group of 14 leading economists, published an e-book </caption><url href=\"http://www.voxeu.org/sites/default/files/file/P248%20inflation%20targeting%207%20may.pdf\" platform=\"highweb\"/></link>and the general conclusion - not shared by all of them - included this: ","markupType":"candy_xml","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"&quot;It (inflation targeting) is needed now more than ever to keep expectations anchored while the advanced economies work their way through today's slow growth, rickety banks, and over-indebted public sectors.&quot;","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"For now, that seems to be the view of most central banks. There are certainly challenges to what you might call the 'inflation targeting consensus', but so far it has survived them. ","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"}]},"promo":{"headlines":{"shortHeadline":"Inflation targeting: Has it worked?","headline":"Inflation targeting is 25 years old, but has it worked?"},"locators":{"assetUri":"/news/31559074","cpsUrn":"urn:bbc:content:assetUri:news/31559074","curie":"http://www.bbc.co.uk/asset/0a41ec64-9125-1e4d-8df0-eb8a805d3ac0"},"summary":"Inflation targeting is now 25 years old, and while there are challenges to central banks' 'inflation targeting consensus', so far it has survived.","timestamp":1571223844293,"byline":{"name":"By Andrew Walker","title":"BBC World Service Eco